
🎹 Virtual Piano Program in C

A simple C program that plays musical notes using keyboard keys (A–L, Z–M).

Introduction

This program simulates a virtual piano in the C programming language.
Each key on the keyboard corresponds to a musical note.
It uses the Beep() function from <windows.h> to generate sound frequencies.

Code Explanation

1. Includes <stdio.h>, <conio.h>, and <windows.h>.
2. Uses getch() to detect key presses without Enter.
3. Beep(frequency, duration) plays sound.
4. A–L keys play notes from C to D (higher).
5. Z–M keys play even higher octave notes.
6. Q key exits the program.

Program:

#include <stdio.h>
#include <conio.h>   // for getch()
#include <windows.h> // for Beep() and Sleep()
 
int main() {
    char ch;
    printf("Mini Piano Program 🎶\n");
    printf("Press keys A–L to play notes.\n");
    printf("Press Z, X, C, V, B, N, M for higher notes.\n");
    printf("Press Q to quit.\n\n");
    while (1) {
        ch = getch(); // get character without Enter
 
        if (ch == 'q' || ch == 'Q') {
   printf("\nExiting... Goodbye!\n");  break }
        switch (ch) {
            case 'a': case 'A': Beep(261, 200); printf("C\n"); break;   // C
 case 's': case 'S': Beep(293, 200); printf("D\n"); break;   // D
 case 'd': case 'D': Beep(329, 200);
  printf("E\n"); break;   // E
case 'f': case 'F': Beep(349, 200); printf("F\n"); break;   // F

case 'g': case 'G': Beep(392, 200); printf("G\n"); break;   // G
case 'h': case 'H': Beep(440, 200); printf("A\n"); break;   // H case 'j': case 'J': Beep(493, 200); printf("B\n"); break;   // B case 'k': case 'K': Beep(523, 200); printf("C (High)\n"); break; // C5
case 'l': case 'L': Beep(587, 200); printf("D (High)\n"); break; // D5
             // Higher octave (Z–M keys)
case 'z': case 'Z': Beep(659, 200); printf("E (High)\n"); break; // E5
case 'x': case 'X': Beep(698, 200); printf("F (High)\n"); break; // F5
case 'c': case 'C': Beep(784, 200); printf("G (High)\n"); break; // G5
case 'v': case 'V': Beep(880, 200); printf("A (High)\n"); break; // A5
case 'b': case 'B': Beep(987, 200); printf("B (High)\n"); break; // B5
case 'n': case 'N': Beep(1046, 200); printf("C6\n"); break; // C6
case 'm': case 'M': Beep(1174, 200); printf("D6\n"); break; // D6
   default: printf("Invalid key! Press A–L or Z-M.\n");        break;
        }
    } return 0;
}




Program Output

Expected Output:

🎹 Virtual Piano Program 🎶
Press keys A–L to play notes.
Press Z–M for higher notes.
Press Q to quit.

When you press keys:
A → C note
S → D note
D → E note
…and so on.
Each key plays a unique Beep sound.



Sample Key and Frequency Table

A → 261 Hz (C)
S → 293 Hz (D)
D → 329 Hz (E)
F → 349 Hz (F)
G → 392 Hz (G)
H → 440 Hz (A)
J → 493 Hz (B)
K → 523 Hz (C High)
L → 587 Hz (D High)
Z–M → Higher octave notes.



Conclusion

This project demonstrates how simple sound-based programs can be made using C.
It helps understand the use of getch(), Beep(), and switch-case.

Extensions:
• Add graphical piano keys using graphics.h or GUI library.
• Include melodies by sequencing notes automatically.


